The paper deals with graph algorithms and sparse matrix methods, which are commonly studied in computer science subfields such as data structures (cs.DS), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), numerical analysis (cs.NA), computational complexity (cs.CC), and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on Breadth-First Search (BFS) and the GraphBLAS library also suggest a connection to parallel and distributed computing (cs.DC). However, given the emphasis on algebraic methods and sparse graphs, the first five categories are the most likely.
